# Lab: This One or That One?

> You and a friend are at a busy street food stand choosing what to order and what to take to the table. Practice quick choices with lots of `este/esta/estos/estas`, `ese/esa/esos/esas`, and `esto/eso`.

## Roles

A: Cliente 1
  You are close to the counter and point at items near you

B: Cliente 2
  You are a bit farther back and ask for clarification constantly

## Turns

A: Point to two nearby items and compare
   (Use one masculine and one feminine noun)
   - Este... | This...
   - Esta... | This...
   hint: Este taco se ve bien, pero esta salsa pica mucho.

B: Point to items farther away and compare
   (Use `ese/esa`)
   - Ese... | That...
   - Esa... | That...
   hint: Ese jugo se ve mejor y esa torta esta mas grande.

A: Choose between plural options near you
   (Use `estos/estas`)
   - Estos... | These...
   - Estas... | These...
   hint: Estos tacos son para nosotros y estas cebollas tambien.

B: Reject one option and choose farther plural options
   (Use `esos/esas`)
   - Esos... | Those...
   - Esas... | Those...
   hint: Esos no, mejor esas quesadillas de alla.

A: React using neuter forms
   (No noun after `esto/eso`)
   - Esto... | This...
   - Eso... | That...
   hint: Esto esta perfecto, pero eso no me convence.

B: Ask for handoff practice
   (Force contrast: near me vs near you)
   - Pasame este... | Pass me this...
   - No, ese... | No, that...
   hint: Pasame este plato. No, ese plato, el de la orilla.

A: Clarify one final order using four forms
   (Use `este`, `esa`, `estos`, `esas` in one response)
   - Este..., esa..., estos..., esas...
   hint: Este refresco, esa salsa, estos tacos y esas servilletas, por favor.

B: Close with two neuter judgments
   (Evaluate the whole order)
   - Esto... | This...
   - Eso... | That...
   hint: Esto ya quedo bien. Eso era lo que queria.

## Tips

- If there is a noun right after, do not use `esto/eso`.
- Say the noun out loud first, then pick the form that matches gender and number.
- In fast conversation, speakers switch between near/far forms constantly. Keep practicing contrast pairs: `este/ese`, `esta/esa`, `estos/esos`, `estas/esas`.
- Use `esto/eso` to react to ideas, flavors, prices, or whole situations.
